I think one is following the wrong stereotype if anyone thinks an archeologist wouldn't want to know what's inside a jar. Archeologists aren't by default ardent preservationists who'd want to keep things sealed up and buried. They open things up, prod the contents, take notes and samples, then restores the artifact.

The Osiris Jar would almost certainly be presumed to be a canopic jar containing a dessicated organ from a mummified body or some items of household life like spices or cloth. The last thing an Earth archeologist (aside from Doc Jackson) would think was inside was a living alien organism with a penchant for taking over a human being's body.
